  "text": "## Dashboard JSON Schema Version Migration Pipeline\n\nThe Grafana dashboard migration system implements a comprehensive pipeline for evolving dashboard JSON schemas from version 0 through version 42 (the final version for the v1 dashboard API). The system operates across three layers: backend Go migration runners, the versioned migration function registry, and a frontend TypeScript mirror implementation.\n\n### Backend Architecture\n\n**Migration Runner**: The core orchestration occurs in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/migrate.go`. The `Migrate()` function serves as the entry point, coordinating the entire migration process. It calls `Initialize()` to set up dependencies and manages the sequential application of schema version migrations from the input version to the target version.\n\n**Migration Function Registry**: The `GetMigrations()` function in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migrations.go` (lines 36-80) returns a map[int]SchemaVersionMigrationFunc containing all registered migrations, keyed by version number. This registry maps schema versions 2-42 to their corresponding migration functions. Notable examples include:\n- V33(dsInfoProvider) - Takes a DataSourceInfoProvider dependency\n- V36(dsInfoProvider) - Migrates datasource references from legacy string format to structured UID-based objects\n- Standard migrations: V2 through V42\n\n**Individual Migration Steps**: Each schema version has a dedicated implementation file (v2.go through v42.go) in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/`. For example:\n- `v2.go` implements `V2()` function handling legacy services.filter structure migration\n- `v36.go` implements `V36()` function transforming datasource references to UID-based objects\n\nThese functions follow a consistent signature: `func V{N}(ctx context.Context, dashboard map[string]interface{}) error`.\n\n**Utilities and Helpers**: `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/migration_utils.go` provides type conversion utilities (GetStringValue, GetBoolValue, GetIntValue, GetFloatValue, ConvertToFloat, ConvertToInt) and data access helpers ensuring safe type assertions throughout the migration pipeline.\n\n### Frontend Implementation\n\n**DashboardMigrator Class**: The TypeScript frontend mirrors backend logic in `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardMigrator.ts`. This class exports `DASHBOARD_SCHEMA_VERSION = 42` and implements the `updateSchema()` method (lines 103-759) which programmatically applies all schema version migrations (oldVersion < 2 through oldVersion < 42) to dashboard objects. Each version check (e.g., `if (oldVersion < 2 && finalTargetVersion >= 2)`) corresponds to a backend migration step.\n\n**DashboardModel Integration**: `public/app/features/dashboard/state/DashboardModel.ts` instantiates DashboardMigrator in its constructor, automatically running migrations when loading dashboards. The DashboardModel class manages the overall dashboard state and delegates schema migration to DashboardMigrator.\n\n### Migration Flow\n\nThe complete migration chain works as follows:\n1. Backend receives a dashboard JSON with schema version V (e.g., v39)\n2. `Migrate()` calls `GetMigrations()` to get the registry\n3. For each version from V+1 to targetVersion (typically 42), the corresponding migration function is invoked\n4. Each function transforms the dashboard map in-place\n5. Frontend receives migrated JSON and DashboardModel instantiates DashboardMigrator\n6. `updateSchema()` ensures consistency by running the same logic again (idempotent for already-migrated dashboards)\n\n### Schema Versions Scope\n\n- Minimum supported version: 0\n- Latest version: 42 (final for v1 dashboard API)\n- Migration path is strictly sequential (v14→v15→v16...→v42)\n\n### Documentation\n\nComprehensive migration guides are provided in:\n- `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/README.md` - Overall migration system architecture and monitoring\n- `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/schemaversion/README.md` - Detailed instructions for creating new schema migrations, with step-by-step examples and testing strategies\n\nThe conversion system also encompasses API-level conversions between v0alpha1, v1beta1, v2alpha1, and v2beta1 dashboard formats, handled in `apps/dashboard/pkg/migration/conversion/` (conversion.go, v0.go, v1.go, v2.go) with automatic metrics instrumentation and error classification."
